      <!-- AUTHOR NOTE -->
      <div class="author-note">
        <div class="author-avatar">R</div>
        <p><strong>A note from Robert:</strong> I'm 64. I've used Lose It! and understood immediately why it works for people trying to lose weight. The calorie budget is clear, the interface is clean, the gamification keeps people engaged. But as a man over 40 whose primary concern is preserving muscle — not shrinking the number on the scale — the whole frame felt off. This post is the honest explanation of why.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- QUICK ANSWER -->
      <div class="quick-answer">
        <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Lose It! is a <strong>calorie-tracking app built around weight loss</strong>. It's genuinely good at what it does — for that goal</li>
          <li>Most men over 40 focused on muscle preservation need the <strong>opposite mindset</strong>: eat more protein, not fewer calories</li>
          <li>Lose It!'s calorie-deficit framing, gamification, and social features create the <strong>wrong mental model</strong> for muscle preservation after 40</li>
          <li>SnapProtein tracks one thing — <strong>daily protein</strong> — with logging under 30 seconds, no calorie budget, no badges, no social feed</li>
          <li>The right tool depends on the goal: <strong>if the goal is weight loss, Lose It! works. If the goal is protein for muscle, it's the wrong frame entirely</strong></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 — WHAT LOSE IT DOES WELL -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>What Lose It! Actually Does Well</h2>
        <p>Lose It! is one of the most user-friendly calorie tracking apps available. The interface is clean and intuitive. The food database is large. The goal-setting experience is clear and well-designed. It was named the best weight loss app by CNN Underscored for its simplicity, affordability, and ease of use — and that assessment is fair.</p>
        <p>For someone whose primary goal is losing weight through calorie awareness, Lose It! delivers. It keeps a daily calorie budget front and center, tracks exercise, connects to fitness devices, and uses streaks and social features to maintain engagement. At roughly $40/year for the premium tier, it's reasonably priced for what it offers.</p>
        <p>None of that is the problem. The problem is when you use it for a different goal than it was built for. When men over 40 whose primary goal is muscle preservation — not weight loss — reach for it because it's familiar, popular, or what their doctor mentioned, the entire frame of the app works against them.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 — THE FRAME PROBLEM -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>The Frame Problem: Why the Goal Changes Everything</h2>
        <p>This is the most important distinction in this post — and it's one most app comparison articles miss entirely.</p>
        <p>Lose It! is built around one core question: <em>did I stay within my calorie budget today?</em> Every feature, every notification, every visual indicator in the app is organized around calorie deficit. The assumption baked into the design is that you're trying to eat less.</p>
        <p>Men over 40 trying to preserve muscle mass have a fundamentally different goal. The question they need answered every day is: <em>did I eat enough protein today?</em> Not fewer calories — more protein. The direction of the goal is different. The mental model is different. And the tool that solves one doesn't automatically solve the other.</p>

        <div class="frame-grid">
          <div class="frame-card loseit">
            <h4>Lose It! asks every day:</h4>
            <div class="fc-question">"Did I stay under my calorie budget?"</div>
            <div class="fc-answer">Optimized for weight loss through restriction. Calorie deficit is the primary measure of a successful day.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="frame-card snapprotein">
            <h4>SnapProtein asks every day:</h4>
            <div class="fc-question">"Did I hit my protein target?"</div>
            <div class="fc-answer">Optimized for muscle preservation through adequate intake. Hitting the protein target is the measure of a successful day.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>These seem similar. They aren't. They drive opposite behaviors. A man eating 1,600 calories might be under his Lose It! budget — and be 50g short on protein, quietly losing muscle month after month. The calorie app gives him a green light. The protein app would show him exactly where he failed.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <h3>The calorie restriction trap after 40</h3>
          <p>Calorie restriction without adequate protein accelerates muscle loss — the exact opposite of what most men over 40 need. Research consistently shows that men in a calorie deficit who don't meet protein targets lose disproportionate amounts of muscle alongside any fat. <strong>Losing weight without protecting protein means losing the thing that keeps you strong, metabolically active, and physically capable.</strong></p>
          <p>An app that only tracks calories can't tell you this is happening. It just shows you a green budget. It can't show you what it's not designed to track.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="related-link">
          <span class="rl-icon">🔗</span>
          <p>Why protein is the primary lever after 40: <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/how-to-stop-muscle-loss-after-50/">How to Stop Muscle Loss After 50</a> — the two things that actually move the outcome.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 — FRICTION POINTS -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>Where Lose It! Creates Friction for Men Over 40</h2>
